net.sf.appia.core
Class Event

java.lang.Object
  net.sf.appia.core.Event
Direct Known Subclasses:
ApplAsyncEvent, ChannelEvent, CloseTcpSocket, EchoProbeEvent, FIFOConfigEvent, GroupEvent, GroupInit, JGCSJoinEvent, JGCSLeaveEvent, JGCSReleaseBlock, MaxPDUSizeEvent, MessageSender, MulticastInitEvent, NetworkUndeliveredEvent, RegisterSocketEvent, SendableEvent, ServiceEvent, SuspectedMemberEvent, TimerEvent
public class Event
extends java.lang.Object

The class Event is the superclass of all events manipulated by Appia.
The class also performs all the basic functionality, namely that associated with moving through the protocol stack.

Author:
Alexandre Pinto
See Also:
EventScheduler

Constructor Detail

Event

public Event()
Create an uninitialized Event.
The event doesnt have information regarding the Channel to which it belongs, the Direction it will take, or the Session that generated it.
All these attributes must be set, before the event is initialized.

go

public final void go()
              throws AppiaEventException
Sends the event to the next Layer. If the next layer doesn't exist, the event is discarded.
In a protocol Session, after the event is handled, this method should allways be called, unless you have a reason to stop it. This is important for modularity purposes.

Throws:
AppiaEventException

asyncGo

public final void asyncGo(Channel channel,
                          int dir)
                   throws AppiaEventException
Inserts the Event in the Channel asynchronously. This method should be used if the Event is to be inserted in the Channel in response to some asynchronous ocurrence, for example the arrival of a network message.
NOTE: the Event must not be initialized. Any Channel, Direction or source already set are REMOVED.
The Channel and Direction of the Event are given as parameters. The source of the Event is the Channel itself. Therefore if the Direction is UP the the Event will start at the bottom of the stack. Otherwise if the Direction is DOWN the Event will start at the top of the stack.
IMPORTANT: This call could block, if the channel is full of events and a memory manager is being used. This method cannot be called from the Appia thread it self.

Parameters:
channel - the Channel of the Event
dir - the Direction of the Event
Throws:
AppiaEventException
See Also:
MemoryManager
